      <div set:html={`<h2 id="how-to-convert-docx-to-epub-without-losing-formatting">How to Convert DOCX to EPUB without Losing Formatting</h2>
<p>Microsoft Word's DOCX format and EPUB are built on fundamentally different philosophies. Word is a WYSIWYG document editor; EPUB is a reflowable ebook standard. Converting between them requires understanding what transfers cleanly and what doesn't.</p>
<p>This guide walks you through converting DOCX to EPUB with maximum formatting preservation.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="why-docx-to-epub">Why DOCX to EPUB?</h2>
<p>EPUB is the standard format for ebooks. If you've written a book, manual, or long-form document in Word, converting it to EPUB lets readers enjoy it on any ereader or reading app with a comfortable, adaptive reading experience.</p>
<p>The alternative — sending someone a DOCX — requires Word or a compatible editor. EPUB opens on Kindle (with conversion), Kobo, Apple Books, Google Play Books, and dozens of other apps.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="what-formatting-transfers-from-docx-to-epub">What Formatting Transfers from DOCX to EPUB?</h2>
<p>Understanding what survives the conversion helps you <strong>prepare your DOCX before converting</strong> — which is the single biggest factor in quality.</p>
<h3 id="what-transfers-well">✅ What Transfers Well</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Formatting</th>
<th>How It Transfers</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Headings (H1–H6)</td>
<td>Mapped to EPUB heading tags, generates Table of Contents</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Paragraphs</td>
<td>Preserved as block elements</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Bold, italic, underline</td>
<td>Preserved</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Ordered and unordered lists</td>
<td>Preserved (may need verification in output)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Links/hyperlinks</td>
<td>Preserved as clickable links</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Images (inline)</td>
<td>Preserved if embedded in DOCX; external links may break</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Horizontal rules</td>
<td>Preserved</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id="what-transfers-imperfectly">⚠️ What Transfers Imperfectly</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Formatting</th>
<th>Issue</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Multi-column layouts</td>
<td>Collapse to single column in EPUB</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Text boxes</td>
<td>May be lost or repositioned</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Tables</td>
<td>Basic tables transfer; complex nested tables may break</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Page breaks</td>
<td>EPUB uses flow-based breaks, not fixed pages</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Headers and footers</td>
<td>Not typically rendered in EPUB readers</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Track changes / comments</td>
<td>Not transferred</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Custom fonts</td>
<td>May fall back to reader's default font</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Watermarks</td>
<td>Not transferred</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id="what-doesnt-transfer">❌ What Doesn't Transfer</h3>
<ul>
<li>Macros and VBA code</li>
<li>Fill-in form fields</li>
<li>Embedded Excel/Word objects (OLE)</li>
<li>Some complex WordArt and effects</li>
<li>Fixed page numbers (EPUB uses flow-based content)</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2 id="step-by-step-convert-docx-to-epub">Step-by-Step: Convert DOCX to EPUB</h2>
<h3 id="method-1-converter-epubcom-fastest-browser-free">Method 1: converter-epub.com (Fastest — Browser, Free)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Simple-to-medium complexity DOCX files. Fastest method, zero file upload.</p>
<p>converter-epub.com converts DOCX to EPUB entirely in your browser using mammoth.js under the hood. Your files never leave your device.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1: Open converter-epub.com</strong></p>
<p>Go to <strong><a href="https://converter-epub.com/">converter-epub.com</a></strong> in your browser.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Upload Your DOCX</strong></p>
<p>Drag your <code>.docx</code> file onto the converter, or click to browse and select it.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Set Book Title and Author</strong></p>
<p>Enter a book title (required) and author name (optional). These are embedded as EPUB metadata and visible in your ereader's library.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Click "Convert to EPUB"</strong></p>
<p>Wait a few seconds. The browser processes the file locally.</p>
<p><strong>Step 5: Download</strong></p>
<p>Click the download button to save your EPUB file. Test it by opening it in your preferred reading app.</p>
<hr />
<h3 id="method-2-calibre-best-quality-free-desktop-app">Method 2: Calibre (Best Quality — Free Desktop App)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Maximum control, complex formatting, batch conversion, PDF input.</p>
<p>Calibre's conversion engine is more sophisticated than most online tools. It handles edge cases better and gives you granular control over the output.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1: Download and Install Calibre</strong></p>
<p>Download from <a href="https://calibre-ebook.com/">calibre-ebook.com</a>. Available for Mac, Windows, and Linux.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Add Your DOCX</strong></p>
<p>Click "Add books" (green folder icon with +) and select your DOCX file.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Open Conversion Dialog</strong></p>
<p>Right-click your book → <strong>Convert books</strong> → <strong>Convert individually</strong>.</p>
<p>Set the output format to <strong>EPUB</strong> using the dropdown in the top-right corner.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Configure Options (Important!)</strong></p>
<p>Calibre gives you extensive conversion settings. Key ones to check:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Metafloppy (look for your book in the left panel)</strong> — Set title, author, tags, language. This is critical for library organization.</li>
<li><strong>Structure detection</strong> — Calibre tries to detect chapter headings. Set your chapter detection patterns (e.g., <code>h1, h2</code> or <code>Chapter *</code>) to ensure the Table of Contents generates correctly.</li>
<li><strong>Table of Contents</strong> — If Calibre didn't auto-detect chapters, you can manually set heading levels or import a NCX/HTML TOC file.</li>
<li><strong>Input encoding</strong> — Usually auto-detected, but if your DOCX has special characters that look wrong, try setting this manually.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Step 5: Convert</strong></p>
<p>Click <strong>OK</strong>. Calibre processes the file. The time depends on file size.</p>
<p><strong>Step 6: Preview and Verify</strong></p>
<p>Double-click the converted book in Calibre to open the built-in viewer. Check:
- [ ] Table of Contents is populated
- [ ] Headings are styled correctly
- [ ] Images are present
- [ ] Lists are formatted properly</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="how-to-prepare-your-docx-before-converting">How to Prepare Your DOCX Before Converting</h2>
<p><strong>This is the most important step.</strong> Cleaning up your DOCX before conversion dramatically improves the EPUB output.</p>
<h3 id="1-use-heading-styles-not-manual-formatting">1. Use Heading Styles, Not Manual Formatting</h3>
<p>❌ <strong>Don't</strong> manually make text bold and large to simulate a heading.</p>
<p>✅ <strong>Do</strong> apply Word's built-in Heading 1, Heading 2, etc. styles.</p>
<p>EPUB converters detect Heading styles to build the Table of Contents. Manual formatting is invisible to them.</p>
<h3 id="2-keep-lists-as-word-lists">2. Keep Lists as Word Lists</h3>
<p>❌ <strong>Don't</strong> simulate lists using dashes, asterisks, or manual tabs.</p>
<p>✅ <strong>Do</strong> use Word's bullet point and numbered list tools.</p>
<p>Native Word lists convert cleanly to EPUB <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code> elements.</p>
<h3 id="3-embed-images-in-the-document">3. Embed Images in the Document</h3>
<p>If your DOCX references images by file path (e.g., "see image on page 3"), those images won't appear in the EPUB unless they're embedded in the DOCX file.</p>
<p>✅ <strong>Insert images directly into the Word document</strong> using Insert → Pictures.</p>
<h3 id="4-simplify-tables">4. Simplify Tables</h3>
<p>Complex nested tables (tables inside tables, merged cells, diagonal cells) often break in EPUB conversion.</p>
<p>✅ <strong>Keep tables simple:</strong> single-level grids with clear row and column headers.</p>
<p>If your document has complex tables, consider converting them to plain text or simplifying the structure before conversion.</p>
<h3 id="5-remove-page-headers-and-footers">5. Remove Page Headers and Footers</h3>
<p>EPUB readers don't render Word-style headers and footers consistently. They may be dropped or placed unpredictably.</p>
<p>✅ <strong>Move important footer content</strong> (e.g., page numbers, book title) into the main document body, or accept that they'll be omitted.</p>
<h3 id="6-avoid-text-boxes">6. Avoid Text Boxes</h3>
<p>Text boxes in Word don't convert well to EPUB. The text inside may be lost or repositioned.</p>
<p>✅ <strong>Convert text boxes to regular paragraphs</strong> or remove them.</p>
<h3 id="7-check-your-fonts">7. Check Your Fonts</h3>
<p>Custom fonts embedded in your DOCX may not render in all EPUB readers. EPUBs fall back to the reader's default serif or sans-serif font.</p>
<p>✅ <strong>Use standard fonts</strong> (Times New Roman, Arial, Georgia) for maximum compatibility, or accept that custom fonts may not appear on all devices.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="troubleshooting-common-docx-to-epub-issues">Troubleshooting Common DOCX to EPUB Issues</h2>
<h3 id="issue-table-of-contents-is-empty">Issue: Table of Contents is Empty</h3>
<p><strong>Cause:</strong> No Heading styles were used in the DOCX.</p>
<p><strong>Fix:</strong> In your DOCX, select all chapter titles and apply "Heading 1" style. Re-convert.</p>
<h3 id="issue-images-are-missing">Issue: Images Are Missing</h3>
<p><strong>Cause:</strong> Images were linked (not embedded) or in an unsupported format.</p>
<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Re-insert images directly into the DOCX. Use JPEG or PNG format.</p>
<h3 id="issue-formatting-is-messy">Issue: Formatting Is Messy</h3>
<p><strong>Cause:</strong> DOCX had custom styles, text boxes, or complex layouts.</p>
<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Clean up the DOCX following the preparation guide above. For best results, consider manual cleanup of the EPUB using Sigil (free EPUB editor).</p>
<h3 id="issue-special-characters-look-wrong">Issue: Special Characters Look Wrong</h3>
<p><strong>Cause:</strong> Encoding mismatch.</p>
<p><strong>Fix:</strong> In Calibre, try specifying the input encoding manually. UTF-8 usually works for most documents.</p>
<h3 id="issue-lists-didnt-convert-properly">Issue: Lists Didn't Convert Properly</h3>
<p><strong>Cause:</strong> Lists were formatted manually (dashes/tabs) rather than using Word's list tool.</p>
<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Re-create lists using Word's bullet and numbering tools, then re-convert.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="bonus-batch-convert-multiple-docx-files">Bonus: Batch Convert Multiple DOCX Files</h2>
<p>If you have multiple DOCX files to convert, Calibre handles this efficiently:</p>
<ol>
<li>Select all the DOCX files in your Calibre library (Ctrl/Cmd + click)</li>
<li>Right-click → <strong>Convert books</strong> → <strong>Convert in bulk</strong></li>
<li>Set output format to <strong>EPUB</strong></li>
<li>Click <strong>OK</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>Calibre will queue and convert all files. You can set a hot folder (Calibre's "watch folder" feature) to automatically import and convert any DOCX dropped into a specific folder.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3 id="does-docx-to-epub-conversion-lose-formatting">Does DOCX to EPUB conversion lose formatting?</h3>
<p>Some formatting is lost because DOCX is fixed-layout and EPUB is reflowable. Headings, bold, italic, lists, and paragraphs transfer well. Complex elements like text boxes, multi-column layouts, and custom WordArt may not. Preparing your DOCX properly minimizes losses.</p>
<h3 id="can-i-convert-docx-to-epub-on-mac">Can I convert DOCX to EPUB on Mac?</h3>
<p>Yes. converter-epub.com works in any browser on Mac. Calibre also runs natively on macOS.</p>
<h3 id="can-i-convert-docx-to-epub-on-my-phone">Can I convert DOCX to EPUB on my phone?</h3>
<p>Yes. converter-epub.com works on mobile browsers. For more complex conversions, Calibre Companion (iOS/Android) lets you manage Calibre libraries and send books to your device from anywhere.</p>
<h3 id="is-there-a-way-to-edit-the-epub-after-conversion">Is there a way to edit the EPUB after conversion?</h3>
<p>Yes. <a href="https://sigil-ebook.com/">Sigil</a> is a free, open-source EPUB editor for Mac and Windows. It lets you inspect and edit the underlying EPUB HTML/CSS directly.</p>
<h3 id="how-do-i-send-the-epub-to-my-kindle">How do I send the EPUB to my Kindle?</h3>
<p><strong>Via Calibre:</strong> Connect your Kindle via USB, select the EPUB in Calibre, and click the device icon to send it. Calibre handles the MOBI/AZW3 conversion automatically.</p>
<p><strong>Via email:</strong> Send the EPUB as an attachment to your Kindle's email address (found in your Amazon account settings). Amazon converts it to Kindle format during delivery.</p>
